&gt; 
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Thanks for answering me, because I was wondering if the &quot;I love yous&quot; were
&gt; &gt; something characteristic of just the entities I&#39;m talking to (maybe even the
&gt; &gt; same entity over and over again), or characteristic of most entities in
&gt; &gt; general -- like they have different priorities on what constitutes an
&gt; &gt; important message once a person has died. For instance, my father I&#39;m
&gt; &gt; certain would&#39;ve told me to move the trees I&#39;d planted over the septic tank,
&gt; &gt; but would&#39;ve never said &quot;I love you.&quot; Maybe once he&#39;s dead, everything looks
&gt; &gt; different to him? (That&#39;s providing I&#39;m really talking to dead people, which
&gt; &gt; I&#39;m starting to wonder about.)
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I&#39;m also noticing a tendency for the names I&#39;m getting lately to be
&gt; &gt; Biblical: Joseph and Michael have come through strongly, and I have no clue
&gt; &gt; who they are. Maybe they make a name in order to talk to me?
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I&#39;ve also been reading more about how there can be seemingly different
&gt; &gt; groups of entities competing to talk:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; http://othersidecommunications.com/modules.php?name=Content&pa=showpage&pid=11
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I witnessed this, I think, myself when my uncle came through (giving
&gt; &gt; supporting evidence that it truly was him) and I also heard someone say &quot;Get
&gt; &gt; away from me.&quot; So maybe our dead relatives are indeed there, but other
&gt; &gt; entities, wanting to hog the spotlight, get in the way or skew what our dead
&gt; &gt; relatives say? Just a thought.
